i2YYvntWouih3Ic7uMCOyQXsQc7Wqp0kqg4_YzNRma-tVOSjpBhZnE8CC5hU0eIM_kfBTA=\\\",\\\"summary\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating ClassLoader behavior**\\\\n\\\\nI'm exploring the use of `Class.forName(DEFAULT_IMPL_CLASSNAME)` in the Configurator class. It loads fine as it uses the Configurator's class loader. I'm curious about how ServiceLoader works with a custom ClassLoader that has no parent; could it load service classes? Maybe there’s a potential issue if the parent is null. I think modifying to use a ClassLoader denying all resources could help clarify functionality. I also wonder if ServiceLoader needs to load the provider class at all. Let's examine that situation more deeply.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering test class ordering**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about whether I need to reset the `defaultImpl` if it’s already set; that might be tricky. Testing the order is essential, though. Should I create a method for testing and use `@TestClassOrder`? Hmm, that doesn't seem right. Maybe using `@TestMethodOrder` is an option, but I'm not sure. I wonder if I can get the JUnit engine to prioritize test classes by naming conventions. If I name a file like \\\\\\\"AaaaServerEndpoint,\\\\\\\" could that work? It certainly seems worth exploring!\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_d6q0gZcogviHiSQbTT7it7uQ|fc_08469396b1f069470169f0e406b7f08196aa01e9c5907096af\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"rg \\\"ServerEndpointConfig.Configurator|fetchContainerDefaultConfigurator|DefaultServerEndpointConfigurator\\\" /home/vjovanov/c/forge1/metadata-forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.apache.tomcat.embed/tomcat-embed-websocket/9.0.83/main -n | head -100\"}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 22115, \"output\": 2550, \"cacheRead\": 4608, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 29273, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\