ing and use `@TestClassOrder`? Hmm, that doesn't seem right. Maybe using `@TestMethodOrder` is an option, but I'm not sure. I wonder if I can get the JUnit engine to prioritize test classes by naming conventions. If I name a file like \\\\\\\"AaaaServerEndpoint,\\\\\\\" could that work? It certainly seems worth exploring!\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_d6q0gZcogviHiSQbTT7it7uQ|fc_08469396b1f069470169f0e406b7f08196aa01e9c5907096af\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"rg \\\"ServerEndpointConfig.Configurator|fetchContainerDefaultConfigurator|DefaultServerEndpointConfigurator\\\" /home/vjovanov/c/forge1/metadata-forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.apache.tomcat.embed/tomcat-embed-websocket/9.0.83/main -n | head -100\"}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 22115, \"output\": 2550, \"cacheRead\": 4608, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 29273, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1777394655589, \"responseId\": \"resp_08469396b1f069470169f0e3e08d6081969bb87d2f88a7844d\"}, \"toolResults\": [{\"role\": \"toolResult\", \"toolCallId\": \"call_d6q0gZcogviHiSQbTT7it7uQ|fc_08469396b1f069470169f0e406b7f08196aa01e9c5907096af\", \"toolName\": \"bash\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": \"/home/vjovanov/c/forge1/metadata-forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.apache.tomcat.embed/tomcat-embed-websocket/9.0.83/main/extracted/javax/websocket/server/ServerEndpointConfig.java:68:        private Configurator configurator = Configurator.fetchContainerDefaultConfigurator();\\n/home/vjovanov/c/forge1/metadata-forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.apache.tomcat.embed/tomcat-embed-websocket/9.0.83/main/extracted/javax/websocket/server/ServerEndpointConfig.java:136:                this.configurator = Configurator.fetchContainerDefaultConfigurator();\\n/home/vjovan