t need the ServiceLoader iterator to throw an error. Setting the Thread Context ClassLoader to a loader that throws a ServiceConfigurationError could be a way to test this—though I'm unsure. \\\\n\\\\nI wonder if I should set the class loader to null instead, but then I think about the security aspects and dynamic access in the JVM. There are a lot of intricate details to consider in testing and reporting!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Analyzing ServiceLoader Behavior**\\\\n\\\\nI'm considering what happens when a resource isn't included during the image build or runtime—essentially, the ServiceLoader finds nothing, and a fallback occurs. For other tests, can I add a test resource? Removing a library resource seems off-limits. \\\\n\\\\nFor a native image, ServiceLoader automatically registers providers from the classpath during the build. Maybe there's a way to exclude a service provider via the native-image config, though I'm not sure it’s advisable. \\\\n\\\\nUsing a custom SecurityManager seems like a potential solution, but I’m still brainstorming!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Configuring JUnit tests**\\\\n\\\\nI'm considering changing the build.gradle test configuration to prioritize our test first. I’m thinking of configuring the `test` task filter but can't skip other tests. Maybe I could set the system property `junit.jupiter.testclass.order.default` to something custom, which would require a custom class orderer class in the tests. JUnit does support that parameter, but I wonder how it applies to top-level classes versus nested ones. The JUnit User Guide might clarify this for me!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating resource management**\\\\n\\\\nI'm considering the management of resources in the Native image and questioning the file IO temp. Can I customize the Resource URL? It seems we need a simpler approach. Our current empty enumeration should be assessed. I could assert that `NoConfiguratorServiceClassLoader.requestedServiceResource` is true to ensure that ServiceLoader is querying `getResources`. I wonder if adding this for coverage is beneficial. If the native ServiceLoader doesn't query correctly, it might lead to test failures externally, which isn't what I want!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Refining JUnit class order**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking it might be helpful to check out examples of the JUnit class order property in the repository. By doing this, I can get a clearer understanding of how it's implemented and what variations exist. This exploration could clarify best practices and help us refine our approach. Let’s get started and see what we can find in the code!\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_aH0wArUrdp8kQB0s8CvCxoWq|fc_08469396b1f069470169f0e47d23f8819688761fe53a3a16be\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"find tests/src -path '*/src/test/resources/junit-platform.properties' -type f -print -exec sed -n '1,80p' {} \\\\; | head -120; rg \\\"junit.jupiter.testclass.order.default|ClassOrderer\\\" tests/src -n | head -50\"}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 3552, \"output\": 3098, \"cacheRead\": 26624, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 33274, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1777394760114, \"responseId\": \"resp_08469396b1f069470169f0e4493b9c81969cf5563a4c2d8110\"}, \"toolResults\": [{\"role\": \"toolResult\", \"toolCallId\": \"call_aH0wArUrdp8kQB0s8CvCxoWq|fc_08469396b1f069470169f0e47d23f8819688761fe53a3a16be\", \"toolName\": \"bash\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": \"(no output)\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1777394813720}]}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.apache.tomcat.embed:tomcat-embed-websocket:9.0.83/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-04-28T16-